text.tspan: Software modules should be open for extension, but closed

g.title: Rectangle.43
g.desc: Less likely to break existing code
g.text: Less likely to break existing code

g.title: Folded Corner.44
g.desc: Adhering to OCP by creating new modules, which we can use as ...

g.text: Adhering to OCP by creating new modules, which we can use as an extension on the existing code, will result in less bugs and reduces the chance of breaking existing functionality. This causes a higher level of stability in a software system.

g.title: Folded Corner.47
g.desc: To accomplish OCP we often obscure the concrete implementatio...

g.text: To accomplish OCP we often obscure the concrete implementation. This results in less knowledge of a concrete type within a system resulting in fewer conditionals. (See code example of OCP). Fewer conditionals means the code becomes more readable and understandable.

g.title: Folded Corner.28
g.desc: To accomplish ‘open-closed’ we often obscure the concrete imp...

g.text: To accomplish ‘open-closed’ we often obscure the concrete implementation. This results in clients working with the abstract type. Changing the underlying type will not affect the client and thus no client re-compilation is needed.

g.title: Rectangle.40
g.desc: Less likely to break existing test cases
g.text: Less likely to break existing test cases

g.title: Folded Corner.55
g.desc: Violating OCP means modifying existing code. Modifying existi...

g.text: Violating OCP means modifying existing code. Modifying existing code means that the test cases attached to this code need re-evaluation and maybe modification. Re-evaluating and modifying test code increases the time commitment. In contrast, adhering to OCP means that test suite can be extend without modifying the existing tests.

g.title: Folded Corner.66
g.desc: Creating abstractions for each module, to adhere to OCP, will...

g.text: Creating abstractions for each module, to adhere to OCP, will increase the indirections in a software system. Indirections make software complex, because it will be harder to navigate & debug. Complexity results in more time spent, degrades design and introduces bugs.

g.title: Rectangle.74
g.desc: Less system knowledge is required unrelated to the change
g.text: Less system knowledge is required unrelated to the change

g.title: Folded Corner.84
g.desc: Developer X applied OCP. Developer Y can now extend the syste...

g.text: Developer X applied OCP. Developer Y can now extend the system by introducing new modules, without knowing the details on how the system uses it. In contrast, extending and not having OCP in place, often means we are adapting existing code and we are required to know the ‘using’ details.

g.title: Folded Corner.102
g.desc: We have to consider the OCP necessity to not get ‘trapped’ by...

g.text: We have to consider the OCP necessity to not get ‘trapped’ by to many indirections and spent to much time on creating all these abstracts. We can often derive the changing modules via requirements and discussions with the customer.

g.title: Folded Corner.99
g.desc: Dependency injection provides us a way to inject the ‘necessi...

g.text: Dependency injection provides us a way to inject the ‘necessities’ of a module. Injecting these necessities provides a flexible way to extend the behavior of the system with a new module. We can for example inject different behaviors and switch them during runtime (=strategy pattern) or add additional behavior to certain parts of a module (=decorator pattern). In contrast, having composite dependencies, without injecting, means a decrease in the possibility of extension.

g.title: Folded Corner.104
g.desc: To adhere to OCP we often use Depedency Injection. Dependency...

g.text: To adhere to OCP we often use Depedency Injection. Dependency injection provides a way to test our modules in isolation, by using mocks. Testing in isolation means our problem window is minimized to just that module, while we have absolute control over the dependencies it has. Mocking provides a way to ‘simulate’ complex and slow dependency behavior and or dependency construction. This results in easier and faster minimizing the problem window of our module. Minimizing our problem window means we can identify the root cause of failures faster, meaning we spent less time resolving issues.

g.title: Folded Corner.108
g.desc: Polymorphism is defined here and not inheritance. Stand-alone...

g.text: Polymorphism is defined here and not inheritance. Stand-alone Inheritance makes the base implementation tightly coupled with the derived, because the base implementation cannot be changed by the derived modules. Polymorphism provides this flexibility of change (e.g. virtual & override).

g.title: Folded Corner.125
g.desc: Templates and generics provide a way to change the type of a ...

g.text: Templates and generics provide a way to change the type of a module, without modifying its internals. This can be used to extend the system with a new type of module with the same internals without having to modify the existing system.

g.title: Rectangle.129
g.desc: As a ‘side’ effect, reusable code is often produced
g.text: As a ‘side’ effect, reusable code is often produced

g.title: Folded Corner.65
g.desc: Modules that adhere to OCP often use dependency injection and...

g.text: Modules that adhere to OCP often use dependency injection and polymorphism. Dependency injection often goes hand in hand with interfaces. A module getting an interface injected is capable of being re-used more easily, because we can inject different concrete implementations, as long as we adhere to the interface. Polymorphism goes hand in hand with inheritance. Inheritance makes it possible to share functionality among different concrete implementations.
